  "text": "Preparation of RNA. Glasswares and solutions for the preparation of RNA were first treated to remove RNase as described previously [CITATION_1] . Mycelia of the organism were harvested as described above. An approximately 300-l volume of wet mycelia was resuspended in a 2-ml screw-cap plastic tube in 400 l of homogenization buffer containing 4 M guanidinium thiocyanate, 0.1 M Tris-Cl (pH 7.5), and 1% ␤-mercaptoethanol. A 300-l volume of acid-washed glass beads (400-m diameter; Sigma) and 400 l of a phenol-chloroform-isoamyl alcohol (25:24:1) mixture were added. The cells were broken in a sonicator (Ultrasonic Processor XL; Heat Systems, Farmingdale, N.Y.) at full speed for three cycles of 2 min of beating at 4°C and 2 min of chilling on ice. The mixture was centrifuged at 14,000 ϫ g for 5 min in an Eppendorf microcentrifuge. The aqueous phase was transferred to a new RNase-free 1.5-ml Eppendorf tube and extracted once more with the phenol-chloroform-isoamyl alcohol mixture. The nucleic acid was precipitated by the addition of 1/10 volume of 3 M sodium acetate (pH 5.3) and 3 volumes of cold 100% ethanol at Ϫ80°C for 30 min. The nucleic acid was centrifuged at 14,000 ϫ g in an Eppendorf microcentrifuge for 10 min at 4°C, and the pellet was washed once with 1 ml of 70% ice-cold ethanol. The nucleic acid was air dried and resuspended in 100 l of H 2 O. DNA was then removed by treatment with RNase-free DNase I (Boehringer Mannheim) as described by Huang et al. [CITATION_2] .",
